Defendant Ann M Kessenich in court with attorney Darryl E. Smith.  Patricia I. Daugherty appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Sentencing proceeded.  Statements by the State, defense and defendant. 

Court finds state has complied with victim notification.

AS TO COUNT 1:
Sentencing proceeded.  Statements given by the state, defense, and the defendant.

Court sentenced defendant to serve 1 YEAR in the House of Correction consecutive to any other sentence.  COURT ORDERED TO BE SERVED STRAIGHT TIME, NO RELEASE PRIVILEDGES.  Court gives credit for 0 days served.  Court is opposed to electronic monitoring.

Court STAYED sentence and placed defendant on PROBATION for 3 YEARS.

AS TO COUNT 2:
Sentencing proceeded.  Statements given by the state, defense, and the defendant.

Court sentenced defendant to serve 1 YEAR in the House of Correction consecutive to any other sentence.  COURT ORDERED TO BE SERVED STRAIGHT TIME, NO RELEASE PRIVILEDGES.  Court gives credit for 0 days served.  Court is opposed to electronic monitoring.

Court STAYED sentence and placed defendant on PROBATION for 3 YEARS.


CONDITIONS OF PROBATION ON COUNTS 1 AND 2:

- Serve 30 DAYS UP FRONT CONDITION TIME CONSECUTIVE, in the House of Correction - NO RELEASE PRIVELGES. (COUNT 1 ONLY)

                          REPORT IN DATE:   MONDAY JULY 6, 2015 BY 10:00 AM.

- 11 MONTHS, IMPOSED and STAYED, CONSECUTIVE in the House of Correction to be used by the agent for any violations.  Defendant shall serve 30 days for the first violation, 60 days for the second violation, and THE BALANCE for the third violation.  AS TO COUNT 1 ONLY.

- 1 YEAR, IMPOSED and STAYED, CONSECUTIVE in the House of Correction to be used by the agent for any violations.  Defendant shall serve 30 days for the first violation, 60 days for the second violation, and THE BALANCE for the third violation.  AS TO COUNT 2 ONLY.

- Complete a mental health evaluation and comply with any recommended treatment.
- AODA assessment and comply with any recommended treatment.
- Maintain absolute sobriety, no alcohol, no controlled substances without a valid prescription, with random drug tests and breathalyzers.  
- Obtain all prescriptions from one pharmacy.
- Seek and maintain full time employment, school, or a combination of both.
- No association with known drug users or dealers, and no contact at any place where illegal drugs are purchased, used, stored, packaged, or distributed.
- Complete 50 hours of community service. (50 HOURS TOTAL FOR BOTH COUNTS)
- Court ordered defendant to provide a DNA, and pay all MANDATORY COURT costs, fees, surcharges, and assessments, while on probation.  Any amount remaining due and owing is subject to civil judgment and/or tax intercept or other means.  Defendant to make regular monthly payments.
- Pay all supervision fees.  Defendant to make regular monthly payments.

Defendant Ann M Kessenich in court with attorney Darryl E. Smith.  Antonella Aleman appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  

Amended Information filed.  Copy given to defense counsel who waived reading.  Defendant pled not guilty.

AS TO THE AMENDED INFORMATION ON COUNTS 1 & 2:
Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, and plead GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights and Addendum received and filed.  Stipulation by parties to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis to sustain the plea.  Court found the defendant guilty.  Judgment of conviction entered.
  
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess any gun or other firearms. 
Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.  

Court also advises defendant if he is not a citizen of the United States of America, that upon a plea of guilty or no contest for this offense, he could be deported, excluded from admission to his country, or denied naturalization under federal law.  
Court advised that the defendant will have to provide a DNA sample, to the Wisconsin State Crime Laboratory for DNA testing.
